I"U <p>This post details how to connect a Beaglebone Green (BBG) to the internet.
Actually, this should work for almost any of them.</p>

<h2 id="1-macos">1. MacOS</h2>
<p>Instructions for getting started with the BBG are available at at
at <a href="https://beagleboard.org/getting-started">https://beagleboard.org/getting-started</a>. Unfortunately, for
the latest version of MacOS (I’m using Big Sur 11.2.1), the drivers
cannot be installed. The easy way to connect is:</p>
<h3 id="step-1-macos-to-bbg-connection">Step 1. MacOS to BBG Connection</h3>
<p>Connect your Mac to the BBG using both the microUSB and Ethernet (you will need an Ethernet adaptor for your Mac and a cable). Use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">screen</code> to login to the BBG on your Mac and then type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ifconfig</code>. On my machine (the “phwl@PHWL-MBP ~ %” prompt is for my Mac and the “debian@beaglebone:~$” prompt is on the BBG) it is done as follows:</p>

<div class="language-sh highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>phwl@PHWL-MBP ~ % screen /dev/cu.usbmodemBBG2200804786
